[White "1. Main Level"]
[Black "Repertoire Introduction - Why this Subject?"]
[Result "*"]

{ Following the  (ongoing at the time of writing)  2018 Candidates Tournament in Berlin, I noticed an interesting pattern in the opening. The Catalan was being played extensively, and White was consistently getting absolutely no advantage. However, the interesting bit, to me, was that Black was achieving these results using lines that were previously ignored by theory, namely 7 Qc2 b6 and 7 Qc2 c6. These are largely modern inventions, ignored by  (as far as I'm aware)  all Catalan books thus far. These developments are covered in Chapters One and Two. The remainder of the chapters are dedicated to completing the repertoire, e.g. everything that isn't the absolute main line with 7 Qc2. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Main Level"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
{ Signaling Black's intention to play, possibly depending on circumstances, either some sort of Nimzo-Indian, Queen's Indian, Bogo-Indian or Queen's Gambit Declined. }
3. g3
{ This is generally seen as an invitation to the Catalan opening, although it can also be reached via. 3 Nf3 d5 4 g3. The Catalan is technically a variation of the QGD, but it's also very much relevant to Nimzo/QID players, as in the current position, Black's best move is generally seen to be 3...d5, transposing to the QGD Catalan. His other options are 3...Bb4+  (the Bogo-Indian, solid but a bit passive)  and 3...c5  (the Benoni - probably more justified here than in other positions, but still not to everyone's taste)  . }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ Welcome to the world of the Catalan - a strategic opening where White attempts to use his Bishop on g2 to cause Black all sorts of annoyances on the Queenside. The main lines can be anywhere from "Black crawls into a shell and braces for impact" to "Black grabs a pawn and hangs on for dear life". I've chosen a middle-road approach for this repertoire - solid, but also active, aiming for counterplay in the centre. }
4... Be7
{ 4...dxc4 and 4...Bb4+ are both fully playable and serious alternatives, but this repertoire will concentrate solely on the text move. }
5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O
{ For a QGD player, this position can also be reached via 1 d4 d5 2 c4 e6 3 Nf3 Nf6 4 g3 Be7 5 Bg2 0-0 6 0-0. }
6... dxc4
{ 6...c6 would be the "crawl into a shell" approach I mentioned earlier - ...b6, ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7 usually follows, when Black is pretty solid, but I don't find his position especially fun to play. Instead, 6...dxc4 is one of the modern main lines - Black temporarily cedes the centre, but will quickly attempt to free his position by breaking with ...c5. }
*

