1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Main Level"]
[Black "7 Qc2 a6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2
{ This is White's main line, although 7 Ne5 is also quite popular, and rather tricky to deal with. }
7... a6
{ This is currently the main line, although it isn't one of the moves I'll be recommending in this repertoire. There's nothing wrong with it; many many elite players have chosen it, and  (somewhat less impressively)  , I've also played it a number of times. That being said, a couple new and interesting lines have come to the fore, and I'd like to hop on those trends before they become fully mainstream. }
8. Qxc4 { 8 a4 is also a move, when Black generally goes ...Bd7-c6. } 8... b5
9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bd2
{ Excellent move - here is Black's main problem in this variation. His c7 pawn is currently backwards, and he has less space. The break ...c7-c5 would solve both of those problems and give him equality. However, }
10... Nbd7
{ ...preparing ...c5 like this is excellently met by 10 Ba5!, freezing the c-pawn, followed by b2-b4, locking it in place, when White has reason to hope for a strategic advantage. Black isn't forced to play 10...Nbd7 by any means  (nor is it such a horrible move, actually)  , but it's scenarios like this to keep in mind when looking at my recommended lines - stopping ...c5 is somewhat less easy. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Main Level"]
[Black "7...b6 - Intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6
{ This is the first of my two recommended moves in this position, covered in Chapter One. I've called it the Bukavshin Variation, after the late Grandmaster Ivan Bukavshin, who died tragically young. Black simply wants to play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5 whilst White is re-gaining his pawn. Black has less space on the Queenside than after ...a6/...b5, sure, but he also doesn't have to worry about Bd2-a5, nor a2-a4. This is such a fresh variation that Avrukh's 2015 Catalan work doesn't mention a word about this variation. Perfect for surprise value! }
8. Qxc4 Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 c5
{ This is just an illustration of Black's plan in action, where he should equalize. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Main Level"]
[Black "7...b6 8 Ne5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
{ You may have been wondering about this move when I brought up 7...b6. It's probably the most important way to disturb Black's ...Bb7/...Nbd7/...c5 set-up, as we are now impelled to sacrifice an exchange. }
8... Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5
{ Black has good compensation - this was recently tested in the game Ding Liren-Caruana, from the  (at the time I'm writing this)  ongoing Candidates Tournament. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
