[Black "7...c6 - Intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6
{ This is my second recommendation, covered in Chapter Two. I've called it 'The Karjakin Variation', as he's wheeled it out a couple of times in the, again, as of the time of writing, ongoing Candidates Tournament. Sergey's point is that he wants to push ...b5, play ...Bb7 and eventually ...c5, but with the pawn already on c6, he doesn't have to worry about the Bd2-a5 maneuver. This line is arguably even fresher than the 7...b6 variation, and again, Avrukh's book appears to predate its popularity. }
