[White "2. 7 Qc2 - The Bukavshin Variation"]
[Black "8 Ne5 - Part 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
{ As I mentioned in the introduction, this is the critical move. White opens his Bishop along the h1-a8 diagonal before Black has a chance to station his own. If the Bishop is allowed to get to b7, ...c5 will soon follow, and White generally has a harder time setting Black any problems. }
8... Qxd4
{ This exchange sac is one of the main points of this variation - 8...Nd5 9 Qxc4 wouldn't be as fun. Now, White should really take the Rook, but sometimes he opts not to, as we'll see. }
*

