1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
Qxd4 9. Qc3
{ This is possible, but not terribly ambitious - White is just trying to win back his two pawns. }
9... Qxc3 10. Nxc3 Nd5
{ Good move - c6 immediately winds up getting the Queen's Rook trapped  (see the next informational)  . }
11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bxd5 c6 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 14. Bxc6 Bh3
{ An important move - otherwise the Rook is trapped after Rb8 15 Bf4, at which point Bh3 would lose the a-pawn  (after 16 Bxb8 Bxf1 17 Bxa7)  . }
15. Bxa8 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 Rxa8
{ Black is at least equal, and probably a little better - the advanced Queenside majority is a nice asset for the endgame. }
