1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5
{ This is the key position of, arguably, the whole 7...b6 line. } 10. Qxc4
{ This is logical, but not very good, for a specific reason. } 10... Ba6
{ This is the problem - the e2 pawn gets skewered off, which not only leaves Black with two pawns for his exchange, but also weakens the f3 square. }
11. Qc3 Qxe2 12. Re1 Qh5
{ Black is better - he isn't even down material, and has Kingside attacking chances as well as activity in the centre/Queenside with moves like ...c5 and ...Nd5. }
13. Qxc7
{ This greedy move isn't very good, but it's worth checking to make sure it doesn't work. 13 Bf3 is better, but after 13...Qf5, my computer tells me that Black is doing very well. }
13... Ng4 14. h4 { Weakening, but forced. } 14... Bc5 15. Be3
{ Again, sad but forced. Now the most powerful might be: } 15... Nxe3 16. fxe3
f5
{ Black is barely down any material, while it looks like White is about to be torn limb from limb after ...f4. }
