10... Nd5
{ This is probably the right way to go. Ba6 covers the pawn, but it's rather awkward. First of all, White can go 11 Bf4, and you end up having to stick your Queen on some weird square on the Queenside. In the meantime, the Bishop on a6 is covering the pawn, but not doing much else. This is basically just a long-winded attempt to explain what computers and top players have concluded about this position. Nd5 centralizes a Knight and stops the uncomfortable Bf4. }
11. Qxc4 Ba6
{ Again, importantly, e2 is covered or none of this would work for White. } 12.
Qb3 Nc6
{ A good choice - after c5, the awkward move is 13 Nc3!, when the threat on d5 compells Black to play Nxc3. The problem is that 14 bxc3! actually makes it more difficult to Black to push his Queenside pawns or find good squares for his pieces. The text threatens to pop the Knight into d4 and take on f3, which would make the Light Squares rather weak. }
13. Qa4 { Avoiding the ...Nd4 "fork", and hitting two pieces. } 13... Bb7
{ Fortunately, the long diagonal is kind of where this Bishop wants to be anyways. }
14. Nc3 Nd4
{ Good move - this essentially "wins" White's Light Squared Bishop for the Knight "by force". This is pretty helpful in Black's quest for tangible counterplay. }
15. Bxd5
{ Sort of forced - allowing Black to take on f3  (or even win the e2 pawn)  would've gone significantly worse. }
15... exd5 *

