[White "2. 7 Qc2 - The Bukavshin Variation"]
[Black "8 Ne5 - Part 11 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 10. Bf3 Nd5 11. Qxc4 Ba6 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. Qa4 Bb7 14. Nc3 Nd4
15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Qxa7
{ Greedy, but Black has to react precisely to keep his initiative going. }
16... Ba8
{ Good move - put the Bishop on a square where it's A  still on the long diagonal; B  not blocking the c-pawn and C  securely defended. Now, ...Nxe2+ is the threat... }
17. Bf4 Qh5
{ I think it's a bit much to look at every possible variation, but suffice it to say that Black's threat is either to take on e2 or sacrifice his Knight on f3  (more on this in a second!)  and barring that, his plan is ...Ne6/...d4, Queen to the long diagonal, and mate on g2. }
18. Bxc7 Nf3+
{ Boop! A typical trick for these types of positions, also seen in the Ding Liren-Caruana game itself. After White takes the Knight, Black is getting his Queen to f3 and playing ...d4 very quickly, and mate is on the horizon. The following is more or less forced: }
19. exf3 Qxf3 20. Rae1 d4 21. Ne4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Qxe4
{ After White takes on b6, Black will be a pawn down, but his advanced passed d-pawn gives him excellent compensation. I kind of doubt memorizing this far is especially useful, but it's fun  (and instructive)  to see the various mating motifs Black can attempt, and how they fare against best defense. }
