1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 10. Bf3 Nd5 11. Qxc4 Ba6 12. Qb3 Nc6 13. Qa4 Bb7 14. Nc3 Nd4
15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Bf4 Qf6
{ After 17 Bxc7, there is 17...Nf3+!? 18 gxf3 d4 and ...Qxf3, similar to the line we've just seen, but my computer tells me 17...Bc5! is even stronger. }
17. Rad1 c5
{ Cementing the Knight, and incidentally, moving the c-pawn out of attack. Again, ...Ne6 and ...d4 is the plan, opening the long diagonal and possibly gaining tempi along the way. }
18. Be3
{ Now 18...Ne6 would simply run into 19 Nxd5, as there is no ...Nxf4. However, Fabi hits him with a nice idea: }
18... Nf3+ { Excellent move! } 19. exf3 d4
{ Black is a Rook down for a pawn, but White's minor pieces are forked, and ...Qxf3-g2# is looming. }
20. f4 { 20 Bf4 dxc3 is also alright for Black. } 20... dxc3 21. bxc3 Bf3
{ Black had obvious and beautiful compensation for the exchange on the Light Squares in Ding Liren-Caruana, Berlin Candidates 2018, which was eventually drawn. The blunt long diagonal battery isn't even the only mating idea: ...Qh6-h3-g2# is also in the air, as in the variation 22 Qxa7 Qh6 23 Qd7 f5! and wins, shown on the live broadcast of this round. }
