1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Ne5
Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 10. Bf3 Nd5 11. Qxc4 Ba6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Re1
{ Simply defending the e2 pawn. Here, the game Aronian-Hou Yifan, Tibsili 2017 went 13...b5 14 Qe4, with an eventual Queen trade. While this is probably okay for Black, as I mentioned earlier, I generally prefer to start with ...c4 to avoid this possibility. }
13... c4
{ This position is completely untested as far as I can tell. Here's a random computer generated variation: }
14. a3 b5 15. Qc2 Nc6
{ ...Nd4 is in the air. After 16 Qe4, Black can either exchange Queens or avoid it with a move like 16...Qf6, with activity, strong Queenside pawns, and dynamic compensation in either case. }
16. Qe4 *

