1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Qxc4
{ A natural enough move - White simply recaptures his pawn, electing not to engage Black in the exchange sac he's offering. That being said, it's also not especially challenging. }
8... Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 c5
{ I mentioned this line in the introduction as an illustration of Black's plan. Now, White can proceed in a few different ways: }
11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b4
{ Now, in the game Bu-Bacrot, Tbilisi 2017, Black found a nice tactic to win a pawn: }
12... Bxf2+
{ Going back with 12...Be7, and then playing ...a5 and claiming b2-b4 is an overextension is also a pretty decent approach. }
13. Kxf2 Rc8 14. Qf4
{ This is the best move - after something like 14 Qb3, Black has 14...Rxc3! anyways, based on the fork on e4. }
14... Rxc3 15. Bb2 Rc7 16. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Unfortunately forced, otherwise something will be left hanging. Black is a pawn up, but White admittedly has decent compensation. }
