Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 c5 11. Ne5
{ This was played by Aronian in round 9 of the Candidates, and also previously by another 2600+ player. }
11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Qc8
{ Sidestepping Nc6xe7 and setting up a potentially useful check on the long diagonal. It also clears the d-file, which is a relevant factor, given that 12...Nxe5?? 13 dxe5 would cost a piece straight away. }
13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. dxc5 Qc6+ 15. f3
{ In Fridman-Rambaldi, Bergamo 2016, White played 15 e4. In that game, Black tried ...a6, ...b5 and then ...Bxc5, as there's not really any rush to take back on c5 straight away. However, ...Qxc5, as in the Aronian-Mamedyarov game, is also perfectly valid. }
15... Qxc5
{ 15...a6!? might be valid here as well, if you want to keep things a bit more complicated. }
16. Qxc5 Bxc5
{ Black had no particular problems holding this position in Aronian-Mamedyarov, Berlin Candidates 2018. }
