1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Bg5
Nd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qxc4 Ba6
{ I know I said something about the Bishop not belonging on c4 earlier, but in this case, it's doing well. It's annoying the Queen, and pinning the e-pawn once it moves away. }
11. Qc2 Nd7
{ As usual, ... c5 is our break, and as usual, it makes sense to start with ...Nd7. c5 is also fine, but I find it's a slight annoyance to have to take on an isolated pawn after either 12 dxc5 bxc5 or Rc8 13 Nc3 Rxc5 14 Nxd5 exd5. }
12. Nc3 Nxc3
{ c5 was played in Studer-Bacrot, Biel 2017, and looks totally acceptable for Black. That being said, if you want to play ...c5 quickly you often end up having to take on an IQP or hanging pawns  (after the captures on d5 and c5)  , which in my opinion is just a bit unpleasant for Black. }
13. bxc3 c5
{ Now we get kind of a Grunfeld/Semi-Tarrasch type of structure, but a better version than usual, I think. First of all, Black's slight space disadvantage is compensated for by the two sets of exchanged minor pieces. Furthermore, the Bishop on g2 doesn't exactly make a ton of sense if White is planning on playing e2-e4 at some point. After an eventual ...cxd4, cxd4, Black has a Queenside majority and a potential target on a2 to work with. }
14. Rfe1 { Unpinning  (and supporting)  the e-pawn. } 14... Rac8
{ Black has several acceptable ways to continue. This is one of them: } 15. Qb2
{ Black was threatening to split White's pawns by going ...cxd4 at a moment when cxd4 in reply would hang the Queen. }
15... cxd4 { Nf6 16 Qa3! is something to be careful of. } 16. cxd4 Rc7
{ Followed by doubling with ...Rfc8, with equality. } *

