12. Rd1 c5 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Rac8 15. Qb2
{ This position was seen in the game Socko-Deac, Graz 2018. It's identical to the previous variation, except that White's Rook is on d1 instead of e1. This works against him, as ideas such as Qb2-a3 aren't really on the table, because e2 would hang. }
15... Nf6
{ cxd4 and Rc7 is equally possible here, but I quite like the way Deac handled this. }
16. a4 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nd5
{ Planning either ...Nc3   xe2!  or simply ...Qb4, attempting to exchange Queens into a pleasant ending  (majority + isolated a-pawn)  . }
