1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Bg5
Nd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. e4
{ This aggressive move was the choice of two 2700+ players, and thus obviously must be taken seriously. }
10... Nb4 11. Qc3
{ One of White's problems in this line is that 11 Qxc4 is always running into the Ba6 skewer. }
11... c5 12. a3 N4c6 13. d5 Na5
{ Good move - the Knight temporarily looks silly on a5, but it lends support to c4. In the near future, it will likely either be exchanged off, or hop to b3 and then d4. }
14. Nbd2 Ba6 15. Ne5 Nd7
{ Now, White has a choice - take the pawn straight away or play more ambitiously. }
16. f4
{ An ambitious move - White anchors his Knight on f4, whilst refusing to regain his pawn at the cost of simplification. Unfortunately for White, he may wind up regretting not taking on c4 while he had the chance. }
16... Nxe5
{ In Wei Yi-Deac, Black played Nf6, which was far from bad, and in fact he ended up beating his Super GM opponent. The text however, is a computer-suggested improvement, which makes life even more difficult for White. }
17. fxe5 { 17 Qxe5? c3 just wins material. } 17... Nb3
{ The Knight is heading from the passive a5 square to the beautiful d4 square. Importantly, 18 Nxb3 cxb3 gains a tempo on the Rook. }
18. Rad1
{ If instead 18 d6, we can simply play Qd7, when the protected passer isn't doing much, and we've gained the option of ...Qa4, to support the c4-pawn. }
18... Nd4 19. Rfe1
{ Importantly, White is compelled to abandon the f-file to stop ...Ne2+. If instead 19 Rf2, we have exd5 20 exd5 Qxe5. }
19... f6
{ Not wanting to allow White to calmly re-take on c4, Black blasts open the centre, creating serious counterplay down the f-file. The computer continues the line, but I'm satisfied to stop here, and suffice it to say Black has an excellent position. }
