1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Nbd2 c5 11. dxc5 Na6 12. Nb3
{ It looks as though White might have enough resources to defend his pawn with Nb3 and Be3, but of course Karjakin has worked out in advance that he can get his pawn back. Here's how: }
12... Be4
{ Good move - luring White's Queen to c3, so that when Be3 is played, Black has ...Nd5xe3. }
13. Qc3
{ You could put the Queen somewhere else as well, but then Black just takes on c5 with a totally healthy position. }
13... Rc8 14. Be3 Nd5
{ This, again, was the point of making White stick his Queen on c3. } 15. Qd2
Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Nxc5 18. Nxc5 Bxc5
{ Black had equalized in Caruana-Karjakin, Berlin Candidates 2018. Actually, this same variation showed up on the board in one of my blitz games a couple of days after this game was played. }
