1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Nc3
{ This is the most natural move, and can probably be considered the "main line" of this young variation. }
10... Nbd7 11. Rd1
{ Indirectly fighting against ...c5 by placing the Rook on the soon-to-be-opened d-file. }
11... Qb6
{ Black, sensibly, hops off the d-file, while lending support to the b7 Bishop, b5 pawn and c5 square, all of which are a great assistance in making the ...c5 break work. White now has a few different tries, none of which should really trouble Black unduly. }
