1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. Ne5
{ This was So's attempt against Mamedyarov, but it shouldn't really lead anywhere. }
12... Rfd8
{ Opening the d-file with 12...Nxe5 is also possible, but seems a bit compliant. 12...Rad8 is worth considering as well, but in the game the c-file opened up, so it makes sense to leave the Queen's Rook untouched, so as to go to c8 when the time is right. }
13. Be3 Nd5
{ A logical response - annoying the Bishop and stopping any d4-d5 ideas White may be planning. }
14. Nxd5 cxd5
{ This change of structure is not necessarily unfavourable to Black. Admittedly, he no longer will be able to play ...c6-c5 and clear the Bishop's diagonal, but White's Bishops aren't exactly doing great work themselves. }
15. Rac1 Rac8
{ Black had no particular problems in the game So-Mamedyarov, Berlin Candidates 2018. }
