1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. e4
{ This is pretty much the most ambitious move, but it also allows Black some dynamic counterplay. }
12... c5
{ The computer points out that 12...h6 is also possible, but this seems too passive as a reaction to a move like e2-e4. }
13. d5 c4
{ This is an idea borrowed from some lines of the Meran. Black clears c5 for a Knight or Bishop  (Knight could hop into d3, while Bishop targets f2)  , while allowing dxe6, when ...fxe6 opens the f-file for the Rook, making the f2 pawn wince just a bit more. }
