1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. e4 c5 13. e5
{ White has always played 13 d5 in practice, but this move could well be more challenging. }
13... Nd5 14. Bg5
{ This is a little awkward for Black - the threat is Nxd5 and Bxe7, while Bxg5 15 Nxg5 makes it difficult to cover h7 in a convenient way, and f6 is obviously fairly weakening. After letting it run for a bit, however, the computer shows the path to equality. }
14... Nb4 15. Qb1 Bxf3 16. Bxe7 { 16 Bxf3 Bxg5 } 16... Bxg2 17. Bxf8
{ On 17 Kxg2, Black can simply play Rfc8, with a dynamically balanced position. Giving up the Dark Squared Bishop wasn't ideal, but we have excellent counterplay on the Queenside and against White's centre. }
17... Rxf8 18. dxc5
{ This is pretty much forced - if you try to grab the exchange on f8, Black will get ...cxd4 and ...Nxe5 in, White's centre collapses, and Black is actually much better. }
18... Qb7 19. Rxd7 Qxd7 20. Kxg2 Qc6+ { Winning the pawn back, with equality. }
