[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 7 Qc2 - The Karjakin Variation"]
[Black "10 Rd1 - Part 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. Ne5 Nxe5
{ This is the simplest option. The problem with our usual move 11...Qb6 is 12 Be3! - the Bishop opposite our Queen can lead to tactical problems, and we don't have ...Nd5 this time because d7 would hang. }
12. dxe5 Nd5
{ This move is stronger than the passive 12...Nd7 if we can get away with it, which, in this case, we can. }
13. e4 Nb4 14. Qe2 Qc7 15. Nc3
{ 15...Qxe5 is too greedy - Black runs into various tactical problems involving Bf4 and Rd7! Check it with a computer, White already has a winning advantage there. }
15... Rfd8
{ Black is fine. After a2-a3, the Knight simply goes back to a6, from where it can re-emerge on c5, and perhaps later b3. White has a space advantage, yes, but it's hard for him to get anywhere on the Kingside with, say, f4-f5, with the e5 pawn potentially being a target and simplification likely to occur along the d-file. }
