b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ 11 Nc3 would, of course, transpose to 10 Nc3 Nbd7 11 Bg5. The text is another attempt to hold up ...c5 by swinging the Knight over to b3. By now, he know how to react... }
11... c5 { Excellent move! } 12. Bxf6
{ Now, taking back with a piece might allow White to grab on c5. Fortunately though, the doubled pawns aren't too much of a concern for us. }
12... gxf6 13. Rac1 Qb6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nb3
{ This is the game Vitiugov-Riazantsev, St Petersburg 2017. Significant because the Black player in this game is the second of none other than Sergey Karjakin. Here the computer suggests a slight improvement on Black's play: }
15... Rac8
{ Black is doing excellently - his Bishop pair and active pieces more than compensate for his doubled pawns. }
