[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 7 Qc2 - The Karjakin Variation"]
[Black "Catalan - 9 Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qb3
{ Chessable user IndekR suggested I include a recommendation against Christoph Sielecki  (chessexplained)  's 'Keep It Simple' repertoire, with includes several branches of the Catalan. My impression is that 9 Qb3, Sielecki's recommendation, which was not initially covered in the course, seems like a more logical move than than 9 Qc2, for a few reasons. In fact, it is odd that I didn't cover it - even though it has been less popular than the alternative 9 Qc2, it was even played in the Candidates Tournament this repertoire and course were inspired by  (a big victory for Karjakin against Aronian, which we will address)  . White's Queen seems just better placed on b3 than c2, as it is out of the way of c-file pressure. ...Bb7-e4 attacks, and ... Nd5-b4 attacks. }
9... Bb7
{ Okay, well this seems logical enough - it's the way we meet 9 Qc2 as well. }
10. Rd1 Nbd7
{ My first thought was to hop off the d-file with 10... Qb6, but it seems like White indeed has some annoying pressure after Nc3/Be3 or Bg5. Therefore, Black should probably start with 10... Nbd7, as it's not clear the Queen is even particularly well-placed on b6, given some of White's ideas. }
11. Ne5
{ I assume this is generally White's point with this whole variation. The idea is that, unlike the analogous variation with the Queen on c2, Black lacks the idea to jump to d5 and then to b4, attacking White's Queen. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ A key game in this line is the game Caruana-Duda, Tata Steel 2020  (very fresh theory !)  , which I think we should follow for a few moves, before I will suggest a deviation. }
13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Nd2
{ This is the aforementioned Aronian-Karjakin game  (Berlin Candidates 2018)  . White's idea this time is to get the Knight to e4 without exposing it to an attack with ...b5-b4. Therefore, 14... Nc5 isn't quite as strong here, when it can't be followed up forcibly with ...b4 and ...Ba6. Therefore, we'll follow Karjakin's game for one more move. }
14... Rfd8 15. Ne4 Nc5 16. Nxc5 Bxc5 17. Rac1 Bf8
{ Black just isn't particularly under pressure here. Black gets to carry out ...c5 without all that much resistance, either right away on the next turn, if the tactics work Qxb5, ...Bxg2, Kxg2, ...Rab8 and .. .Rxb2 is one idea, , or even by starting with ...a6, and then going for it.   18.Qxb5  immediately does not work because of  18...Rxd1+  19.Rxd1  cxb5  . }
*

