{ Black continues to make threats, and now White starts being pushed back. }
16. Nb1
{ Plausibly White is going to play something like Nd2-c4 and/or a2-a3. This was Caruana's choice. }
16... Ba6
{ Well, I mean, if Black isn't being allowed to play ...c5, may as well activate this Bishop in a different fashion. This also stops Nd2 for the moment, due to attack on the e2 pawn, which Caruana addresses with his next move: }
17. Bf3
{ After letting my computer run to depth 45 this morning, its main line was the weird looking move 17 Re1!?, which I think is way less natural than Caruana's move, but nevertheless it gave something like +0.22, so I figured I should mention it. Nevertheless, this looks like an unnatural computer-y move, but also I don't even really see, from a human perspective, why I'd rather put my Rook on e1 than my Bishop on f3. Black can probably proceed as in the main line. }
17... Rfd8
{ In the game, Duda played 17... Rac8?!, which I suppose he regretted because he half-retracted it with his next move. I suppose Black should put a Rook on the d-file, but there are still some complications. Either Rook to the d-file seems acceptable, but I guess this one makes mildly more sense  (presumably the a8 Rook has a greater potential function on a8, b8 or c8 than the f8 Rook would on f8 or e8)  . }
18. a3 b3 { White's idea kind of backfires here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. 7 Qc2 - The Karjakin Variation"]
[Black "Catalan - 9 Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 8. Qxc4
b5 9. Qb3
{ Chessable user IndekR suggested I include a recommendation against Christoph Sielecki  (chessexplained)  's "Keep It Simple" repertoire, with includes several branches of the Catalan. My impression is that 9 Qb3, Sielecki's recommendation, which was not initially covered in the course, seems like a more logical move than than 9 Qc2, for a few reasons. In fact, it is odd that I didn't cover it - even though it has been less popular than the alternative 9 Qc2, it was even played in the Candidates Tournament this repertoire and course were inspired by  (a big victory for Karjakin against Aronian, which we will address)  . White's Queen seems just better placed on b3 than c2, as it is out of the way of c-file pressure. ...Bb7-e4 attacks, and ... Nd5-b4 attacks. }
9... Bb7
{ Okay, well this seems logical enough - it's the way we meet 9 Qc2 as well. }
10. Rd1 Nbd7
{ My first thought was to hop off the d-file with 10... Qb6, but it seems like White indeed has some annoying pressure after Nc3/Be3 or Bg5. Therefore, Black should probably start with 10... Nbd7, as it's not clear the Queen is even particularly well-placed on b6, given some of White's ideas. }
11. Ne5
{ I assume this is generally White's point with this whole variation. The idea is that, unlike the analogous variation with the Queen on c2, Black lacks the idea to jump to d5 and then to b4, attacking White's Queen. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7
{ A key game in this line is the game Caruana-Duda, Tata Steel 2020  (very fresh theory !)  , which I think we should follow for a few moves, before I will suggest a deviation. }
13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Nc3 Nc5
{ Black exploits the fact that White's Queen is placed on b3 to gain a tempo in a different way. In fact, Black has to play very actively, as otherwise he just ends up with a long-term weakness on c6, and a passive Bishop on b7  (unless he manages to push ...c5, which seems difficult at the moment due to the b5 pawn hanging)  . }
15. Qc2 b4
{ Black continues to make threats, and now White starts being pushed back. }
16. Nb1
{ Plausibly White is going to play something like Nd2-c4 and/or a2-a3. This was Caruana's choice. }
16... Ba6
{ Well, I mean, if Black isn't being allowed to play ...c5, may as well activate this Bishop in a different fashion. This also stops Nd2 for the moment, due to attack on the e2 pawn, which Caruana addresses with his next move: }
17. Bf3
{ After letting my computer run to depth 45 this morning, its main line was the weird looking move 17 Re1!?, which I think is way less natural than Caruana's move, but nevertheless it gave something like +0.22, so I figured I should mention it. Nevertheless, this looks like an unnatural computer-y move, but also I don't even really see, from a human perspective, why I'd rather put my Rook on e1 than my Bishop on f3. Black can probably proceed as in the main line. }
17... Rfd8
{ In the game, Duda played 17... Rac8?!, which I suppose he regretted because he half-retracted it with his next move. I suppose Black should put a Rook on the d-file, but there are still some complications. Either Rook to the d-file seems acceptable, but I guess this one makes mildly more sense  (presumably the a8 Rook has a greater potential function on a8, b8 or c8 than the f8 Rook would on f8 or e8)  . }
18. Nd2 Nd7
{ This is a pawn sacrifice, but Black ends up with clear compensation, e.g. }
19. Qxc6 Qxc6 20. Bxc6 Rac8 21. Bxd7 Rxd7
{ ...and now the attack on the e2 pawn either allows Black to re-gain his material, or gives him time to get his Rook to c2. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "Intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5
{ This is White's other 'main line'. It's arguably a bit more aggressive than 7 Qc2, and often leads to messy positions. Black has to be very careful not to drift into passivity, after e.g. 7...Nbd7 8 Nxc4, which I remember walking into in a few blitz games a few years ago, and the Bishop on g2 is a monster, while its counterpart struggles to develop. }
7... Nc6
{ Okay, this might require a bit of explanation. Basically, Black is trying, by whatever means necessary, to activate his Queenside pieces, even if it means giving the pawn back, or allowing tripled  (!)  pawns. Play tends to be rather unorthodox and theoretical, but the simpler alternatives, in my opinion, are frankly depressing. I've played 7...c5 a couple of times, and got interesting games, but against best play, Black is stuck defending a slightly worse position, with no winning chances. Anyways, 7...Nc6 has emerged over time as a clear-cut preference among strong players - it just works, what else can I tell you?  Note that for this chapter I made fairly heavy use of Jan Gustafsson's chess24 video series 'A repertoire against 1.d4. Part 1: Dealing with the Catalan' - in some places I've quoted his recommendations, while in others I've substituded lines I feel are simpler. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Nxc6 - Part 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6
{ By far the most natural move, but, somewhat surprisingly, it is fairly evenly split with the alternative 8 Bxc6 in terms of popularity. }
8... bxc6 9. Bxc6
{ Again, the most natural, but this isn't really supposed to be critical. The point is that the c6 pawn is less important than the c4 pawn, so allowing Black to exchange off the powerful Catalan Bishop with ...Rb8 and ...Bb7 isn't worth grabbing back this pawn. }
9... Rb8 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7
{ This is a pretty typical position - Black's structure isn't the greatest, but White's King is potentially weak, while Black is quite active, and likely about to liquidate one of his doubled pawns with ...c5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Nxc6 - Part 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. e4 c5 { As advertised. }
13. d5
{ Pushing gaining space - 13 dxc5?! instead is already a bit better for Black after 13...Bxc5 - White has problems developing his DSB without hanging b2, and Black is very active. }
13... Rd7
{ Excellent move - now, Gustafsson in his chess24 Catalan videos for Black, gives the following variation: }
14. Qe2 exd5 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Rxd5 17. Qxc4 Bf6
{ Black's activity  (and even attacking chances with ...h5-h4; White misses his LSB)  compensates fully for his worse pawn structure, as in Bangert-Schott, Germany 2002. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Nxc6 - Part 3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bxc6 Rb8 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Rxb7 12. e3 c5 13. Qf3
{ 13 dxc5 Bxc5, as usual, is excellent for Black. This is trickier, however. After the natural 13...Rd7, White has 14 dxc5 Bxc5 15 Qf4, winning the c4 pawn. }
13... Qa8
{ This is one of a few decent moves - Black is simply intending to play ...Rc8, covering the pawn when it's attacked. Again, it is generally rather important to keep the c4 pawn alive in these lines. }
14. Qe2 cxd4 15. exd4 Rc8
{ Black was at least equal in Polyakov-Solozhenkin, Hersonissos 2017. } *

