1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3
{ This is considered White's main try these days. You just kind of have to believe me here. Anyway, White's going for the c4 pawn, which we shouldn't allow, so... }
9... Bxa3
{ 9...Ba6 10 Qa4 is pretty inconvenient when you don't have ...Bb5 in reply. }
10. bxa3
{ Okay so, both sides' structures are pretty horrible, and this is a pretty confusing position. We're still a pawn up for the time being, but chances are overwhelming that the c6 pawn falls off the board at some point. However, the good news is that the c4 pawn which White could've captured at will a few moves ago is now passed, so we should try hard to keep it. }
10... Ba6
{ Defending the pawn and preparing to answer 11 Qa4 with 11...Bb5. 10...Nd5 11 Qa4 Nb6 used to be the main line, but the computer doesn't like this - apparently allowing Qa4xc6 isn't such a good idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Nxc6 - Part 5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Bxc6
{ Again, this is the most obvious move, but nowadays top players have mostly switched to the more subtle 11 Qd2!?. }
11... Rb8 12. Qa4 Rb6 13. Bf3 Nd5
{ Centralizing the Knight and introducing various possibilities of ...Nc3 or ...c3. It's important that White really play 14 e4, because, not only of 14...Nc3,but 14...Qf6! is actually even stronger. }
14. Qa5 { Stopping ...Nc3 antics. } 14... f5
{ ...and in turn, Black stops White from playing e2-e4. Play is roughly balanced - here's how Black is likely to complete development: }
15. Bd2 Qd6 16. Rfb1 Rfb8
{ ...with roughly equal chances in a complex position. } *

