[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Nxc6 bxc6 9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Ba6 11. Qd2
{ This is a weird-looking move, but it's become essentially the main line in this position. The idea is to bring the Queen over the a5 and put pressure on the Black Queenside. To some degree, it's come to the fore out of necessity, as White hasn't really been finding anything elsewhere. }
11... Rb8 12. Qa5 Qc8 { Covering the Bishop and preparing ...Rd8. } 13. a4
{ Clearing the way for Ba3, after which the Bishop may show up on c5. } 13...
Rd8 14. Ba3 { Now, I agree with Gusti that the simplest move is... } 14... c3
{ 14...Rxd4 was possible, and has been tested in some high-level games, but it's actually a bit awkward for Black after 15 Rfb1, attempting to take over the b-file, while after 15...Rb6 there is 16 Bc5. Black's two pawns up, yeah, but they aren't exactly the healthiest pawns in the word, and White has a lot of positional trumps. With the text, Black activates his somewhat depressing Bishop  (which was stuck guarding the c4 pawn)  . As we've previously seen, exchanging the c4 pawn for the e2 pawn is generally a pretty decent idea. }
15. Qxc3 Bxe2 16. Rfe1 Ba6
{ Black's still a pawn up. White can take it back with a move like 17 Bxc6, but, as usual, it's not really worth allowing the Catalan Bishop to be exchanged   after  17...Bb7  just to recapture the sickly c6 pawn. }
17. Rab1 Rb6
{ As Gustafsson points out, Black is attempting to provoke a4-a5, to give the Queen's Bishop a nice landing spot on b5. Meanwhile, the f6 Knight can hop into the nice d5 square. Play is roughly dynamically balanced. }
