Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4
{ Okay, so we can't exactly save the c4 pawn. However, Black's activity and ability to make threats  (both on the Kingside and directed towards White's Queen)  should enable him to equalize. }
11... e5
{ Good move - freeing Black's pieces  (particularly the Bishop on c8)  . By the way, 11...c5 is well met by 12 Qa3 - this becomes relevant later. }
12. Qxc4
{ I thought I should quickly point out that this is not the right way to take the pawn. }
12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Qxe2
{ If you've clicked through Chapter One, you know the importance of the e2 pawn when the Kingside Light Squares are weak. This is a very dangerous position for White. }
