Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 e5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Nc3 Ne4
{ Excellent move - since 14 Nxe4 Qxe4, allowing the second player to defend his c4 pawn, and inviting the Queen to the long diagonal, is not a particularly good idea, White kind of has to allow his Queenside pawns to be split. Instead, 13...Be6 14 Bf4 gives White the initiative, and time to develop his pieces. }
14. Qxc4 Nxc3 15. bxc3
{ 15 Qxc3 Qxe2 is, as always, not something White should be allowing. You can hypothetically take on c7, however you'll likely get mated pretty quickly. }
15... Be6 16. Qd3 Rad8
{ This was seen in several top-level games, including Hammer-Anand, Kristiansund  (rapid)  2010, which Black actually won, but almost all of the games from here have been draws. }
