{ This is Gustafsson's suggestion. It's also strong, but a little more complicated. }
12. Rd1
{ 12 dxe5 Qxe5 13 Qxc4 would transpose into earlier 11 Qa4 lines, but the text is an independent option. }
12... Bb7 13. Nc3 Qd7
{ This is Jan's main line - the idea is to play ...Qh3 and ...Ng4, and start an attack, at the cost of some pawns. It certainly works out okay for Black, but you really have to know stuff to make it work. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Bxc6 - Part 12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qc2 c5 12. Qxc4 cxd4 13. Qxd4
{ Black's tripled pawns have magically disappeared! Yeah, we're a pawn down, but we've got some short-term attacking chances on the Kingside, and long-term, we really shouldn't be that worried about an ending, as we don't have the ugly split pawns from the other variation. }
13... e5 14. Qh4 { Allowing ...Bh3 would give Black an easier time. } 14... Qb7
{ Good move - Black steps away from any Bg5 pins, while also annoying the pawn on b2. This move has been the choice of Vladimir Kramnik and Michael Adams, which I think is a good enough endorsement. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Bxc6 - Part 13 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qc2 c5 12. Qxc4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 14.
Qh4 Qb7 15. Nc3 Be6 16. Bg5 Ng4
{ This is the way to keep things sort of complicated, and was Kramnik's choice in a blitz game against Wesley So. Otherwise, just exchanging the Knights with Nd5, as played by Adams, should give Black a fairly easy time. }
17. h3 Qxb2
{ This is the point - 18 Nd1 hangs the Rook, while 18 Na4 can be met with the counterattacking Qd4. }
18. Rfc1 { 18 Be7 can just be met with Rfe8, and 19 Ne4 by Qd4. } 18... h6
{ This is sort of the point of Kramnik's play, and the reason why any of this works - the Knight obviously didn't really have anywhere to retreat to. }
19. hxg4 hxg5 20. Qxg5
{ White is temporarily up a pawn, but Black is quick to re-gain it: } 20... f6
21. Qe3 Bxg4 { ...with equality, as in So-Kramnik, Leuven  (blitz)  2016. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
