[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Bxc6 - Part 14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Na3
{ Attempting to win the pawn back with the Knight. } 11... c5
{ e5 12 dxe5 Qxe5 13 Nxc4 with tempo is probably worth avoiding. The other pawn break, however, works fine. Gustafsson's recommendation of Rd8 is also perfectly reasonable. }
12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qh5
{ As is typical, using the weakness of the Light Squares to threaten ...Ng4, provoking f2-f3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. 7 Ne5"]
[Black "8 Bxc6 - Part 15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Ne5 Nc6 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Na3
{ Attempting to win the pawn back with the Knight. } 11... c5
{ e5 12 dxe5 Qxe5 13 Nxc4 with tempo is probably worth avoiding. The other pawn break, however, works fine. Gustafsson's recommendation of Rd8 is also perfectly reasonable. }
12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Be3 Qh5
{ As is typical, using the weakness of the Light Squares to threaten ...Ng4, provoking f2-f3. }
14. f3 c3
{ Good move - this pawn is probably falling anyways  (e.g. Ba6 15 Qa4!)  , so we may as well ditch it while inflicting structural harm. Any potential Opposite Coloured Bishop endings are probably even more drawn now than they previously were. }
15. bxc3 Qa5
{ Switching back to the Queenside to annoy various loose White pieces and pawns. }
16. Qc1 Ba6
{ Black was fine in Kramnik-Anand, Khanty-Mansiysk Candidates 2014. Black can play this a bit like a Marshall Attack, aim for compensation in the middlegame with his activity and his opponent's slightly unsafe King, with the knowledge that he can probably hold any endgame that may arise. }
