[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, we're going to examine the rest of White's options, in order to complete a full anti-Catalan repertoire for Black. However, I won't be covering them nearly as thoroughly as I did the previous chapters, for the similar reason that the first three chapters essentially will cover the grounds of almost all your Catalan games, whereas the lines consigned to this section of the book are less important to understand deeply. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Qa4 - Part 1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qa4
{ This is a perfectly reasonable move, but, as one would expect, Qa4xc4 tends to transpose into Qc2xc4. There is one minor point to mention if you intend on playing the ...b6 system, however. We'll get to that in a minute. }
7... c6
{ If you're playing the Karjakin line from Chapter Two, this move suits your repertoire perfectly. }
8. Qxc4 { Otherwise ...b5 would hold onto the pawn. } 8... b5 9. Qc2 Bb7
{ ...and we're back on familiar grounds. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Qa4 - Part 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qa4 b6
{ This is the way to go if you prefer the ...b6 system from Chapter One; e.g. }
8. Ne5 { 8 Qxc4 would obviously be a direct transposition. } 8... Qxd4 9. Bxa8
Qxe5
{ This leads to quite similar play to the main line of the first chapter. One thing to note is that with the Queen on a4, it's theoretically possible to grab on a7, although it seems ill-advised. }
10. Qxa7 Bd7
{ Cutting off the Queen's retreat square along the a-file. Despite the extra exchange  (for a pawn!)  , I do not envy White's position, what with his pieces stuck in the corner, and potential to be attacked on the Light Squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Nc3 - Intro"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Nc3
{ 7 Nc3 is a move you often see from people who don't know any theory and are just trying to get their pieces out. The Knight doesn't really belong on c3 in this so-called "Open Catalan". The problem is that it makes it significantly harder for Black to get his pawn back, for no particular benefit. Qc2xc4 is now blocked, and Nbd2xc4 is no longer possible. The remaining option is Ne5xc4, which Black should prevent... }
7... Nc6
{ Good move. Now, Black's plan is ...Rb8 and ...b5, to keep his newly acquired extra pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Nc3 - Part 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. e4
{ Logical, occupying the centre, but it doesn't really achieve all that much concretely for White, given his pawn disadvantage. By the way, it's important that Qa4xc4 can't be easily played, as d4 would hang. }
8... Rb8
{ This is probably somewhat stronger than 8...a6, as it clears the g2 Bishop's diagonal. }
9. Be3 b5
{ We could continue this line, but honestly, I'm content to stop here and say that Black is better. White has the centre sure, but what next? e4-e5 allows simply ...Nd5, and White's Bishop on g2 is sorely misplaced for the e4-e5 push  (it would much prefer to be on say, c2)  . That aside, I'm not sure what White's doing to prove compensation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Nc3 - Part 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. e3
{ This is the most popular move - defending the d4 pawn and thus preparing Qa4xc4 or Nd2xc4. }
8... Rb8
{ Preparing ...b5, but again, it's always helpful to have this Rook off the long diagonal. }
9. Nd2
{ Now, the usual ...b5 would hang the Knight, so we have to seek alternative measures... }
9... Na5
{ This may look a bit silly, but it really is worth hanging onto that c4 pawn by whatever means necessary - not only is it an extra one, but there's a non-zero chance it'll Queen thirty moves later. }
10. Qa4 b6
{ This is why it's helpful to have the Rook off of a8! ...Bd7 is coming next, after which Black can push ...b5 and get his Knight off a5. }
11. Nxc4 { A blunder. } 11... Bd7 12. Nb5 { 12 Qc2 Nxc4. } 12... a6
{ ...and Black wins. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "7 Nc3 - Part 4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. e3
Rb8 9. Qa4 Nb4
{ Good move - if 10 a3, then 10...Bd7 makes the Queen go away. The a7 pawn is now hanging, yes, but we'd much rather make White take the a7 pawn than the c4 one, as then his Queen is significantly out of play  (and may even get trapped)  . }
10. Qxa7 Bd7
{ Cutting off the retreat...an idea we've seen in previous a7 grabs in this chapter. }
11. Ne5
{ Threatening to take on b7 or c4, while also setting up a bail-out trap. 11...b5 solves both problems, but after 12 a4, the pawn chain falls apart. }
11... Qc8 { Excellent move - defending b7 and setting up a counter-trap. } *

