1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Na3
{ This is a bit of a weird move. White allows doubled pawns in exchange for the Bishop pair and potential pressure along the b-file. }
7... Bxa3 8. bxa3 Bd7
{ This is given by Jan Gustafsson in his Catalan videos for Black on chess24. Black is simply hoping to slide this Bishop over to c6 to neutralize White's Catalan Bishop. }
9. Ne5 Bc6 { Anyways. } 10. Nxc6 Nxc6
{ The tripled pawns aren't really a worry, as we've seen in Chapter 3. White isn't really well-advised to give up his prized Bishop for the Knight. }
11. Bb2 Nd5
{ Gustafsson stops here, explaining that Black is simply going to play ...Nb6, defend his c-pawn, and be a pawn up. White's Bishops give him some compensation, but it's also worth remembering White ruined his Queenside to get this position as well. }
