1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Nbd2
{ This is really just misguided. If we allow White to re-capture on c4 with the Knight, it might hop into e5 and annoy us. However.... }
7... b5
{ This move is excellent here, as after something like a2-a4 and ...c7-c6, White's Knight is really poorly placed to undermine the pawn chain  (with Na3 and Nc3)  . As well, the move b2-b3, chipping away, is met by ...c4-c3, this time with tempo. }
8. a4 c6 9. Qc2
{ 9 axb5 cxb5 10 Ne5 is met simply by 10...Nd5. With the text, White is planning b2-b3 without ...c4-c3 in reply. If he's able to do this undisturbed, he probably has good compensation. Luckily, however, we do have a good way to disturb him. }
9... Na6
{ Watch out for 9...Ba6?? 10 axb5 cxb5 11 Ng5!, winning material, by the way. }
10. b3 Nb4 11. Qb2 { 11 Qc3 Nfd5 would not be fun for the first player. } 11...
Ba6 { Black was simply a pawn up in Kustanovich-Haslinger, Witley 1999. } *

