1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Nc3 dxc4 7. Ne5
{ This is a line very much comparable to the 6 0-0 dxc4 7 Ne5 of Chapter 3. That being said, having Nc3 in instead of 0-0 contains its own plusses and minuses. It has been played, on occasion, by some very strong players. }
7... Qd6
{ 7...Nc6, as in Chapter Three, is also possible, but I think the text is the simplest way to equalize, and was the choice of none other than Vladimir Kramnik, in a 2015 game against Peter Svidler. Compared to 6 0-0 dxc4 7 Ne5, there, 7...Qd6 is somewhat annoyingly met by 8 Na3 and Naxc4, which is obviously impossible here. This, however, didn't stop Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from trying this version in the last round of the  (now just concluded)  Candidates tournament. }
8. Nxc4 Qa6
{ This is the point. It looks bizarre, but the Queen, first of all, is gaining a tempo on the Knight, while also clearing the d-file for the Rook  (...Rd8 and ...c5)  , and can support a ...b5 push, often followed by a quick ...c5. Hey, if it works, it works, and I don't see how White can do much of anything in this line. }
*

