1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Qc2 c5
{ This is considered to be the best way to exploit White's chosen move order. I'll cover it very briefly, both because 6 Qc2 is a comparative rare variation, and because 6...dxc4 and 7...c6 is my main recommendation. }
7. dxc5 Qa5+
{ This check is the main reason why ...c5 is stronger after 6 Qc2 than 6 0-0. }
8. Nc3
{ 8 Nbd2 would mostly serve to clog up the first player's own development. }
8... dxc4 9. O-O Qxc5
{ Black has won a pawn. Objectively, White shouldn't have any trouble re-gaining the pawn and maintaining equality, but practically, it's already White who has to be careful. Here's a sample continuation: }
10. Bg5 Nc6
{ 10...Nbd7 prevents the idea we'll see, but is quite passive, and White has good compensation after Rfd1 and Rac1. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 { 11...gxf6!? is riskier. } 12. Ne4 Qe7
{ Maintaining contact with the extra c4 pawn would be quite a risky proposition with Nxf6+ and Qe4-h4 looming. }
13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Qxc4 e5 15. Rfd1 Be6
{ Black had no problems in Aronian-Leko, Yerevan 2008. } *

