[Black "6 Qb3 - Part 2 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Qb3 c5
{ This is the independent approach to exploit White's move order. The ideas are more or less the same as in the 6 Qb3 c5 variation, with one difference, due to the differently placed White Queen: }
7. dxc5
{ Here, the ...Qa5+, Nc3, ...dxc4 thing obviously loses much of its point with c4 defended  (even after Nc3)  , so it seems like Black should instead play... }
7... Na6 { ...with ...Nxc5 with tempo next, and a good game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Sidelines"]
[Black "6 Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This is another minor line, this time even rarer. We shouldn't take on c4 and invite White's Knight to c4, and later e5, but instead opt for a slower set-up. }
6... b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2
{ White is playing a set-up normally seen against Black's ...Nbd7/...c6/...b6/...Bb7 variations. However, with the c-pawn still on c7, and White's Queen's Knight sub-optimally placed for an immediate fight in the centre, Black should play... }
9... c5
{ Excellent move! Black is already fully equal. As Gustafsson points out, 10 cxd5 can still be answered with 10...Bxd5, keeping the Bishop's diagonal open. There's not really any theory to know here, but I just thought I'd show one instructive idea: }
10. e3 Rc8 11. Rc1 Rc7 12. Qe2 Qa8 13. Rfe1 Rfc8
{ In Bronstein-Keene, Teeside 1975, Black's pieces were excellently co-ordinated, and all locked and loaded, ready for the opening of the centre. }
*

